<DOCNO> XIE19970629.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Omani Sultan Hold Talks in Red Sea Resort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
started talks with Sultan Qaboos Ben Said of Oman today on the
deadlocked Mideast peace process in the Red Sea resort of Sharm
el-Sheikh, the Egyptian MENA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders held the first session of talks at Sharm
el-Sheikh airport upon the arrival of Sultan Qaboos, before they
drove 35 kilometers to the natural reserve of Ras Mohammed, home
to the rarest coral reefs in the world.
</P>
<P>
"They reviewed the latest Mideast developments, the results of
contacts held by Egypt with different parties concerned, and other
Arab issues," said Minister of Information Safwat Sherif after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Their discussions are also expected to focus on Egypt's
spearheading bids to establish a common Arab market, according to
today's Egyptian Gazette.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and Oman are two members of the Damascus Declaration
whose foreign ministers ended on Thursday discussions at the
Syrian Mediterranean resort of Latakia, agreeing to set up a
common market among the eight signatories to the pact.
</P>
<P>
The visit comes within the context of constant meetings between
the Egyptian and Omani leaderships to boost distinguished ties
between the two countries, the English daily said.
</P>
<P>
Oman was the only Arab Gulf country that kept ties with Egypt
when other Arab states severed diplomatic relations with Cairo in
protest against its 1979 peace pact with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace talks collapsed since March when
Israel started building a new neighborhood for Jews in East
Jerusalem, where Palestinians want as their future capital.
</P>
<P>
Israel captured East Jerusalem from Jordan in the 1967 Mideast
war and then annexed it. The annexation has not been recognized by
most nations.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian and U.S. initiatives have failed to bring the two
sides back to the negotiating table. 
</P>
</TEXT>
