<HEADLINE> Business as Usual for The New SAR, Says HSBC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Prospects for the Hongkong's
Special Administrative Region's (SAR) economy look bright given
rapid growth in both the territory and China, said HSBC today.
</P>
<P>
In an article entitled "Business As Usual For The New SAR", its
Global Markets Weekly said: "Officials from both mainland China and
the territory have repeatedly noted that the current system will
be preserved through 1997 and beyond," so Hongkong's economy's
functioning will "remain the same".
</P>
<P>
The Weekly said, a cornerstone in the territory's financial
system is the linked exchange rate system that was installed in
1983 amid a confidence crisis.
</P>
<P>
Since then, "it has functioned exceptionally well, proving
itself to be able to weather severe financial turmoil," it added.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China (PBOC) recently reiterated that the
HKD will remain a foreign currency in China after July 1st.
Similarly, the Chinese yuan will trade as a foreign currency in
the Hongkong's SAR, the Weekly said.
</P>
<P>
Maintaining this will depend partly on the ability of the
Hongkong Monetary Authority (HKMA) to carry out monetary policies
independently, it added.
</P>
<P>
Expressing its confidence in HKMA, HSBC said: "A recent vote of
confidence in the HKMA's ongoing independence was the invitation
for it to become a member of the Bank for International
Settlements, alongside the PBOC."
</P>
<P>
In addition, Hongkong's huge foreign reserves, which were 66.6
billion US dollars as of end-May, will help fend off any
speculative attack on the HKD, the Weekly said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
