<HEADLINE> WFP Resolves Disputes with Contractors in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World Food
Program (WFP) today paid more than 200,000 U.S. Dollars for
contract termination severance to eight local subcontractors
companies.
</P>
<P>
The payment of 239,747 Dollars was on a compromise deal made
by WFP with the contractors in a bid to settle a long standing
dispute which hampered the relief operation of WFP in Mogadishu,
according to Hugh Hanley, head of WFP's Administration Finance
Section.
</P>
<P>
In a press conference after handing out the money to the eight
local off-loading and transport companies in North Mogadishu
today, Hanley said his agency will now be capable of running its
humanitarian operations which concentrate on food deliveries to
its target areas.
</P>
<P>
Hanley further said the money was not paid under certain legal
systems, but instead paid on negotiation bases with the
subcontractors of WFP's main contractor.
</P>
<P>
The main contractor, Giancarlo Morochino, is an Italian
businessman who handles the off-loading, clearance and storage
facilities for WFP. And he has given subcontracts to these eight
local contractors in facilitating these operations.
</P>
<P>
WFP also has similar problems relating to job terminations and
unpaid wages in South Mogadishu. Hundreds of teachers
demonstrated in front of WFP's main gates in South Mogadishu last
month.
</P>
<P>
The dispute between WFP and the local contractors has resulted
in the disruption of the on-going food aid off-loading at El-Ma,
a natural port, the hijacking of three food convoys early this
month in North Mogadishu and a failed abduction attempt against
WFP personnel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
