<HEADLINE> Jordan Proposes to Set up Joint Bank with Tunisia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul Salam
Majali said today that Jordan and Tunisia may establish a joint
bank to facilitate trade between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Majali made the remarks upon his return to Amman this evening
from a three-day official visit to Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
Majali said that he made the proposal to the Tunisian leaders
when he had talks with them during the visit.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Tunisia tentatively agreed in May to create a
common free trade zone in Jordan and both sides have signed an
accord which provides for a special committee to study the
creation of the free trade zone.
</P>
<P>
The special committee is scheduled to meet in Tunis for the
purpose this month, according to local press.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival in Amman this evening, the prime minister
also said that Jordanian-Tunisian relations are "strong" at all
levels.
</P>
<P>
Majali said that he delivered a message from king Hussein
to Tunisian President Zine Al Abidine Ben Ali and disclosed
that the king will visit Tunisia soon.
</P>
<P>
According to the prime minister, he also held talks with
Tunisian leaders on Arab relations and the stalled Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today at a press conference in Tunis before ending his
visit, Majali noted that Jordan will attend the Middle East and
North Africa Economic Summit due to be held in Qatar in November.
</P>
<P>
By attending the summit, he said, all the parties in the
region will be able to promote their rights, particularly on
economic and refugee issues.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Lebanon have threatened to boycott the conference,
the third since the Madrid Middle East peace conference in 1991,
because of Israeli participation. They argued that the Arab
countries should boycott the meeting as Israel is following its
hardline policy which has stalled the Middle East peace march.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
