<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli High-tech Industries Report Slowdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 28 (Xinhua) -- There has been a slowdown of
growth in the high-tech industry in Israel for the first time in
five years, according to a report of the Israel Export Institute
(IEI).
</P>
<P>
A survey of activities of industrial companies in the economy
published earlier this month by Dun and Bradstreet showed the
trend.
</P>
<P>
The high-tech industry, comprising electronics, programming and
trade in software and hardware, grew by 26 percent in 1996
compared to 32 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
For the past 10 years the share of high-tech industry in
general industrial activity has been increasing steadily. The
high-tech has been Israel's main branch of exports, accounting
for almost 60 percent of Israel's industrial exports.
</P>
<P>
The industry, whose products are mostly destined for export,
has been hit by the high rates of interest in the Israeli
banks. These high rates have forced companies in the Israeli
high-tech industry to become more efficient in order to maintain
high profitability and competitive ability. However, some
companies have recorded a drop in profitability and reduced
competitiveness, particularly against companies from the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Another reason for the drop in growth is the lack of manpower
and the competition within the industry in Israel for
professionals, particularly in the field of software and
electronical engineering. In Israel, there is reportedly a shortage
of between 1,000 and 2,000 programmers and engineers. The
flourishing local start-up branch attracts many staff, and large
companies are today competing with start-up companies for
university graduates. This fact has naturally led to significant
wage rises, which affect the competitiveness of companies to a
certain extent.
</P>
<P>
During 1996 a number of attempts were made to increase the
supply of staff in the industry, both through retraining courses
and by increasing the number of training centers and the capacity
of universities. These steps are likely to reduce the shortage of
staff in the long run, but no short term answer has been found for
the huge demand for workers in high-tech industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970629.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 22 Killed as Terrorist Actions Resumed in Algeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Twenty two people have been killed
near the city of Medea, about 90 kilometers south of the capital
of Algiers as terrorists actions were resumed in the country after
a short period of tranquility.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources here said today that the killing was carried
out yesterday by a group of scores of terrorists equipped with
fire arms.
</P>
<P>
The people being attacked responded by firing shotguns at the
terrorists and managed to kill one of them, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
A bomb planted in a small passenger bus went off some 20
kilometers away from Medea Thursday morning, leaving eight people
dead and 20 others injured.
</P>
<P>
According to eyewitnesses, the bomb was laid inside the bus by
a woman who got off the bus minutes before the bomb blasted.
</P>
<P>
Two bombs exploded at a railway station in the same area
injuring 46 people and damaging several train carriages.
</P>
<P>
Some 60,000 people have been killed and 2 billion U.S. dollars
of material losses inflicted as a result of terrorist activities
in Algeria over the last five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970629.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-28 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Israeli Export Institute (IEI) is
preparing for the introduction of the new European Union (EU) coin
-- the Euro, reported bi-weekly Israel Business Today.
</P>
<P>
The new coin is expected to be in use around the year 2000 and
the IEI is planning to help Israeli companies manage transactions
with European organizations using the new coin.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- A recent Central Bureau of Statistics report
indicates that the average Israeli gross monthly salary at the
end of the first quarter of the year stood at 5,220 shekels (some
1,580 U.S. dollars), reported bi-weekly Israel Business Today.
</P>
<P>
It represented a 0.5 percent increase in real terms on the
figure posted at the end of the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Ergonomic office chair and armchair manufacturer,
Platechnica, is to establish a chair manufacturing facility in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The new plant will be a joint venture together with local
office furniture producer, Tandemex.
</P>
<P>
Platechnica marketing manager Haim Lotzer said that the new
facility is expected to boost company sales in North and South
America to around 7 million U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Oman has signed an agreement to purchase an
Israel-manufactured desalination and tidal hydro-electric system,
reported bi-weekly Israel Business Today.
</P>
<P>
The acquisition was effected via a British marketing
company. Shmuel Ovadia, the owner of the Israeli company which
developed the system, said that the Omani company which bought
the system is owned by the Omani royal family.
</P>
<P>
Ovadia also explained that his company's product is capable of
producing four megawatts of electricity from a 100 meter stretch
of shore and desalinating 500 cubic meters of sea water per hour.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Gold import into Dubai, one of the seven
sheikdoms of the United Arab Emirates (UAE) topped 50 metric
tonnes for the fourth consecutive month with a total import of
52.29 tonnes in May, a local newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The import in May this year is an increase of 57.14 percent
over that of May in 1996, when 33.282 tonnes of gold entered
Dubai, the Gulf News said.
</P>
<P>
The total quantity of gold imported from January to May is
261.627 tonnes, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland, Britain and South Africa are the main gold
exporters to Dubai in the past five monthes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
