<HEADLINE> OIC Urges UN to Enforce Resolutions on Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of Islamic
Conference (OIC) today urged the United Nations to implement all
international resolutions related to Jerusalem, Palestine and the
Middle East Peace Process so as to realize comprehensive and just
peace in the troubled region.
</P>
<P>
This call came in messages from the OIC Secretary General
Ezzedine Laraki to the UN Secretary General Kofi Annan and the
Presidents of both the General Assembly and the Security Council
to mark the 30th anniversary of the illegal Israeli annexation of
Jerusalem, Kuwait News Agency (Kuna) reports from Jeddah said.
</P>
<P>
Laraki appealed for guarantees to ensure the rights of the
Palestinian people to self-determination and the establishment of
an independent state of their own with Jerusalem as its capital,
the reports said.
</P>
<P>
He also drew attention to the illegal actions taken by the
Israeli occupation authorities in Jerusalem including the
confiscation of Palestinian land and properties, the construction
of Jewish settlements and the withdrawal of identity cards of
Palestinians residing in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The OIC Secretariat also sent messages to UN member states
urging them to stress their rejection to Israeli decision of
annexing Jerusalem and to all other Israeli measures taken to
Judaize the city, Kuna added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970629.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Islamic Countries Calls for Sustaining Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, June 28 (Xinhua) -- A two-day meeting of Islamic
countries ended here on Saturday, urging for sustained
international commitment to Bosnia's peace process.
</P>
<P>
The seventh meeting of the Assistance Mobilization Group (AMG)
expressed concern over the continued delay in convening a donors
conference for Bosnia, according to a statement read by Pakistani
Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad, who is also current AMG
chairman.
</P>
<P>
The meeting urged the donor countries to convene the conference
without any further delay and stressed the restoration of economic
and social stability in Bosnia as an integral element for
ensuring lasting peace and reconciliation in the country, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
AMG is part of the Contact Group of the Organization of Islamic
Countries(OIC) to help Bosnia. Besides Pakistan, officials from
Bangladesh, Bosnia, Bruni, Egypt, Guinea, Indonesia, Iran, Jordan,
Kuwait, Malaysia, Morocco, Qatar and Turkey were also present at
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Ahmad said that "the meeting emphasized the need for sustained
international commitment to the peace process which has entered a
crucial phase and decided to recommend to the OIC Contact Group on
Bosnia and Herzegovina to consider convening a Ministerial meeting
at an early date".
</P>
<P>
The participants also called on OIC countries to enhance
economic cooperation with Bosnia, especially through bilateral
assistance.
</P>
<P>
OIC countries pledged 240 million U.S. dollars last year, or 15
percent of the world total for Bosnia's reconstruction efforts,
and they are expected to commit 250 million U.S. dollars this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
