<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clock-Watchers Crowd Onto Tiananmen Square </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- As it ticks down to zero, the huge
countdown clock in Tiananmen Square measuring the moments until
Hong Kong's return is attracting an ever-growing crowd of
spectators.
</P>
<P>
Today, hundreds of thousands of Beijing residents and other
visitors flocked to the clock, mounted on a large white board
against the stone pillars of the Museum of the Chinese Revolution
and the Museum of Chinese History, located on the east side of the
world's largest square.
</P>
<P>
The clock-watchers are expressing their feelings over the
imminent return of Hong Kong in many ways: many wave red paper
miniatures of the Chinese national flag and the flag of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region. Savvy peddlers throughout the
square have hiked up the price of a pair of flags from three yuan
to ten.
</P>
<P>
One young police officer says that the crowd, which has been
huge all week, has swelled noticeably every day. "We are expecting
the largest group today, especially this evening," he says.
</P>
<P>
And like Mickey Mouse in Disneyland, everybody wants their
picture taken near the clock. But photography among the multitudes
requires nimble fingers and saintly patience.
</P>
<P>
Two-year-old Xie Yuqing, balanced on her father's shoulders, is
asked again and again to wave her flags and smile at Mom with the
camera, but they are repeatedly interrupted by passersby who walk
into the view. Finally, Xie's exasperated mother clicks a decent
shot.
</P>
<P>
A tourist from Hong Kong says she's lucky to be in Beijing at
this historic time. "Seeing such a massive celebration in Beijing,
I feel so proud to be a Chinese," says Wong Wai Ting.
</P>
<P>
The clock has been in its place on the square for more than 900
days. It will stop at midnight on June 30, when all its digits
turn to zero. It is estimated that in the more than two years that
have passed, over 10 million people have come to see it.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese are concerned about the clock's future. Beijing
retiree Xu Yingkui, who visited Tiananmen Square today, said, "I
don't know how they will deal with it, but I do hope it will be
kept in a museum."
</P>
<P>
It will be -- but not in the grand Museum of Chinese History
just behind it: The Chinese government has decided to move it to a
spot at the foot of the Great Wall in the northern suburbs of
Beijing, where it will stand as a symbol of China's long journey
toward reunification. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
