<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kai Tak Is World's Busiest Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- With less than 30 hours away
before Hong Kong's return to China, political dignitaries from
various countries, regions and organizations are arriving here to
attend the handover ceremony, making the Kai Tak Airport, already
the busiest in the world, even busier.
</P>
<P>
People are walking in and out of the reserved lounge for
distinguished guests on the second floor. With planes landing
continuously, guests are invited to have a rest there, where they
go through relevant procedures.
</P>
<P>
For the sake of safety, the glass door of the lounge is tightly
closed. A women supervisor of the lounge told reporters on the
other side of the door that the lounge has been fully occupied and
no reporter is allowed in and no interview is permitted.
</P>
<P>
Today and tomorrow, some 800 foreign guests are expected to
arrive in Hong Kong to attend the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Many reporters are at the airport to cover the arrival of these
guests. They often have to wait for two or three hours at the
exit, and after getting the news, they rush out of the airport and
go back by various transportation means to write their stories.
</P>
<P>
The police officers responsible for the security of the airport
are on high alert. A police officer, identified himself as Li,
said that with the many passengers and political dignitaries
arriving these days, the police shoulder a great responsibility.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the safety of the airport and passengers, the police
have been reinforced, he said.
</P>
<P>
As usual, there are large numbers of passengers coming to Hong
Kong. A Mr. He, a U.S. university teacher, came to Hong Kong with
his two children. He said he brought his children to Hong Kong so
that they would be able to witness the historic event of Hong
Kong's return to China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
