<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE Underlines Commitment to Opec Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 29 (Xinhua)-- The United Arab Emirates (UAE)
will continue to commit itself to its oil production quota
awarded by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(Opec), a senior UAE official has said.
</P>
<P>
"The UAE is always working to support Opec policies in
maintaining agreed quotas and prices," said UAE Minister of
Petroleum and Mineral Resources Obeid bin Saif al Nasir, quoted
by UAE's Wam news agency today.
</P>
<P>
He said the UAE would honor its assigned quota of some 2.2
million barrels per day (bpd), hoping world crude prices would
rise in light of all Opec members' adherence to their own assigned
quotas.
</P>
<P>
Nasir returned to the UAE after attending an Opec
ministerial meeting in Vienna last week.
</P>
<P>
Participants agreed to freeze the current Opec production
ceiling of 25.03 million bpd for another six months until
November and maintain assigned quotas of all members.
</P>
<P>
Opec's output, with the exception of Iraq's was set in
September 1993. But the actual output now is running at nearly
27 million bpd because many members are known to have been
exceeding their quotas.
</P>
<P>
This has greatly damaged crude prices which currently hover
around 19 U.S. dollars a barrel, down sharply from 25 dollars in
late 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
