<HEADLINE> Chinese in California Celebrate HK's Return </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 29 (Xinhua) -- More than 20,000 Chinese
Americans gathered in a college stadium here today to celebrate
the return of Hong Kong to China at midnight Monday.
</P>
<P>
The largest ever Chinese gathering in the United States, named
"Welcome Home, Hong Kong Spectacular," was jointly sponsored by
more than 100 associations and guilds in southern California to
mark the end of more than 150 years of British colonial rule of
the island.
</P>
<P>
An congratulatory message to Chinese President Jiang Zemin and
Premier Li Peng was read out at the rally, which said Hong Kong's
return marks "an end to the humiliations the Chinese nation
suffered for more than a century."
</P>
<P>
In another message to the Chief Executive of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region, Tung Chee-hwa, and his six million
fellow residents of Hong Kong, the organizer said they wish Hong
Kong "long-term prosperity" and the island "to shine more
brilliantly."
</P>
<P>
Consul General of the Chinese Consulate General in Los Angeles,
Feng Shusen, and the city's mayor Richard Riordan addressed the
crowd. Feng said that the Chinese government and people are
confident and capable of guaranteeing Hong Kong's long-term
stability, and creating a more prosperous Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Riordan emphasized Los Angeles' role in the U.S. ties with Hong
Kong, the rest of China and the Pacific Rim.
</P>
<P>
The event, beginning with five skydivers landing in the
stadium's field amid colorful smokes, also attracted hundreds of
local Americans.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1997 white pigeons were freed, followed by a parade
of floral floats and marching bands representing 80 organizations.
</P>
<P>
Symphonic music, chorus, dances, martial arts and the
performance of a local concert band enlivened the biggest Chinese
rally in southern California, where more than 800,000 Chinese live.
</P>
<P>
President of the United Chinese Women Organization of USA,
Geogiana Lee, companied by her elder daughter, took part in the
parade. "I want my children, who speak little Chinese, to learn
some history of China from the event," she said.
</P>
<P>
A 30-minute fireworks display brought the spectacular to a
climax. 
</P>
</TEXT>
