<HEADLINE> Legislature Discusses Laws on Higher Education, Flood Control (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Standing Committee
of the National People's Congress (NPC) broke into groups today to
review draft laws on higher education and flood control.
</P>
<P>
Most of the participants in the ongoing 26th session of the NPC
Standing Committee deemed it necessary to have a law to ensure a
healthy development of higher education and standardize the ways
of higher education.
</P>
<P>
However, some insisted that China already has enough
education laws, such as those on teachers, general education and
compulsory education. They felt that much of the content of the
draft law now being studied is identical to that in the existing
law on education, which went into effect in September, 1995. They
proposed to make the draft law a chapter of the existing law of
education.
</P>
<P>
Committee members Xie Songkai and Cai Cheng said that for the
most part the draft law is good, as it reflects the current status
of China's advanced education undertakings and clearly defines the
responsibilities of the governments, schools and society regarding
higher learning.
</P>
<P>
They believed that, after careful deliberation, the law, the
first of its kind in the country, will play an important role
in the development of China's higher education.
</P>
<P>
But Hao Yicun and Dong Ruifang deemed that the draft law lacks
the elements of reform. They held that China's reform in higher
education has not kept pace with the developing market economy,
and is short of regulations and norms in curricula, training and
teacher qualifications as well as their rights and interests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970629.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislature Discusses Laws on Higher Education, Flood Control (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
They said that many teachers have taken to second jobs in their
sparetime, and the teaching profession has lost its attraction in
China. They also thought that the draft law sets a lower standard
for physical and moral education.
</P>
<P>
Dong Naifang said that the making of a higher education law
must aim high and must embody the strategy of invigorating the
nation by developing science and education.
</P>
<P>
Many members of NPC Standing Committee expressed their
dissatisfaction with the State investment in higher
education. "Universities and colleges now can hardly make ends
meet, and they have to make money by all possible means in order
to maintain their routine operation," said Xu Jialu, member of the
Sub-Committee for Education, Science, Culture and Health of the
NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
Xu suggested the draft law on higher education should include
concrete stipulations for the State's investment in the field.
</P>
<P>
In reviewing the draft law on flood control, participants
generally believed that it is a good law, since flood control has
a direct bearing on the safety of people and property.
</P>
<P>
They were virtually unanimous that it is very important to
enact such a law as many parts of the country suffer from flooding
every year.
</P>
<P>
Yang Zhenhui, vice-chairman of the Environment and Resources
Protection Sub-Committee of the NPC Standing Committee, said that
the draft law on flood control should be made one of the basic laws
concerning China's water conservation effort, like the Water Law
and the Law of Conservation of Soil and Water.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his views on the fight against floods and drought
and on comprehensive control of water pollution, the utilization
of water resources and the legal responsibilities of flood
control.  
</P>
</TEXT>
