<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Higher Education Sticks to Party Leadership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The draft law on higher education
that is currently being debated by the national legislature
stresses that colleges and universities should cultivate personnel
who are "both socialist-minded and vocationally proficient."
</P>
<P>
Zhu Kaixuan, minister in charge of the State Education
Commission, told the ongoing 26th session of the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress that higher education
must be guided by Marxism, Leninism, Mao Zedong thought and the
theory of building socialism with Chinese characteristics, and
should be under the leadership of the Chinese Communist Party and
"stick to socialism."
</P>
<P>
"The kind of personnel our universities produce has a great
bearing not only on our country's modernization process, but also
on its long-term stability," Zhu pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The draft law encourages non-governmental organizations to
launch higher education institutes which will supplement State-run
universities and colleges, but stresses that starting such
institutes should serve national and public interest, and not be
driven by profit-making.
</P>
<P>
The State Council gives macro guidance to higher education
while local governments supervise colleges and universities under
their jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
China currently has 2,170 higher education institutes, which
had a total of 5.67 million students in 1996.
</P>
<P>
To make higher education more accessible to females, the
handicapped and students from ethnic minority areas and poor
families, the state will set up scholarships and financial aid
funds.
</P>
<P>
The draft law encourages business enterprises, social groups
and individuals to set up scholarships and funds.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time for the draft to have been deliberated
by the NPC Standing Committee, after the State Council approved it
in May.
</P>
<P>
Also under discussion at the ongoing session is the draft of a
flood control law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970629.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest Gas Field Begins Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Shaanxi-Gansu-Ningxia Natural
Gas Field, China's largest, today began pumping gas to Xi'an, the
capital of Shaanxi Province, via a newly-opened 488-km gas
pipeline extending from northern Shaanxi to the city.
</P>
<P>
The field, located in the Ordos Basin bordering Shaanxi and
Gansu provinces, and the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, was
estimated to have 4.2 trillion cubic meters of natural gas
resources, 500 billion cubic meters of which have been proven.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the pipeline, costing more than 800 million
yuan, started in March last year. The project is expected to
provide natural gas for 710,000 households in Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
Another gas pipeline to Beijing is now under construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
