<HEADLINE> FM: Iran Willing to Improve Ties with Gulf States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Iran today once again voiced its
willingness of forging friendly, healthy and constructive
relations with the Persian Gulf littoral states.
</P>
<P>
The idea was expressed by Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar
Velayati while addressing the opening session of a regional
seminar here on Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The seminar is aimed at reviewing further promotion of
bilateral and regional as well as economic, political and cultural
relations between Iran and eight Persian Gulf littoral states.
</P>
<P>
Velayati outlined Iran's crucial and strategic status in the
world of Islam, according to a report of the official news agency
IRNA.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian foreign minister called for collective efforts
and cooperation to maintain regional stability, security and
tranquility.
</P>
<P>
Iran's ambassadors and representatives to Persian Gulf
countries including Iraq, Yemen, Qatar, the United Arab Emirates
(UAE), Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Oman and Bahrain are attending the
four-day seminar.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the Iranian authorities expressed welcome to the
joint statement of Damascus Declaration foreign ministers meeting
and termed it as a positive sign in relations between Iran and
Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi said that
readiness and interest of the Damascus Declaration states' foreign
ministers in improvement of friendly relations with Iran could
be considered as a positive sign.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi said "such an issue would not only be in line with
expansion of cooperation among regional states, but would be the
sole way of guaranteeing security in the sensitive region of the
Persian Gulf and of helping promote international peace and
security."
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting of foreign ministers of Damascus Declaration
states, which include Egypt, Syria, Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar,
Saudi Arabia and the UAE, ended Thursday in Syria.
</P>
<P>
In the joint statement, the foreign ministers emphasized the
sovereignty of the UAE over the three Gulf islands in its dispute
with Iran, calling on both sides to enter into serious talks for a
peaceful solution to this issue.
</P>
<P>
Today, Major-General Mohsen Rezaee, Commander of the Islamic
Revolution Guard Corps (IRGC), said that Iran is ready to sign
security and defense pacts with its southern Arab neighbors in a
bid to promote security in the region.
</P>
<P>
"We need security because we don't want our vital interests be
jeopardized. We have proved our good intentions." Rezaee said in
an interview with English daily Kayhan International. 
</P>
</TEXT>
