<HEADLINE> Qatar Signs Deal for Economic Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Qatar has signed a memorandum
of understanding with the International Economic Forum to host
the fourth Middle East and North Africa economic conference in
its capital city of Doha, the official Qatari news agency reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The memorandum was signed Saturday at a seminar organized by
Qatar's Chamber of Commerce and Industry, which is being held in
Doha to pave the way for the conference due on November 16-18,
the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The seminar focused on how Qatar can benefit from the
conference, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Qatar is expected to propose at the conference about 30 projects
requiring investment of around 3 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Qatar hopes to invite some 2,500 delegates, including Israeli
businessmen, to the conference.
</P>
<P>
Syria was reported to have tried to assemble opposition to the
conference because of possible Israeli participation.
</P>
<P>
Syria boycotted the previous three conferences because it
believes that Israel should not deserve economic rewards from the
regional conference until it signs peace agreements with all its
Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The previous three economic conferences were separately held
in Casablanca of Morocco in 1994, Amman of Jordan in 1995 and
Cairo of Egypt in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
