<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 12:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qatar to Allow Majority Stakes by Foreigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 29 (Xinhua)-- Qatar is expected to enact a
law soon allowing foreigners to own majority shares in local
projects and companies, a senior Qatari official said today.
</P>
<P>
"The draft law allows foreign entities and individuals to own
more than 51 percent in projects set up with local partners in
Qatar," the Qatari news agency quoted Youssef Hussein Kamal,
undersecretary of the Qatari Ministry of Finance, Economy and
Trade as saying.
</P>
<P>
The law also deals with incentive schemes and provides for
exemption of customs duties for five to 10 years for
projects set up in industrial zones, Kamal said at a seminar
organized by Qatar's Chamber of Commerce and Industry, which is
being held in the Qatari capital of Doha.
</P>
<P>
The draft law has to be approved by the cabinet and the
Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad Ben Khalifa al Thani before it takes
effect, he said. But he did not give the exact date for the
approval.
</P>
<P>
The draft law came within the framework of Qatar's
preparations for hosting the fourth Middle East and North Africa
economic conference due to be held from November 16 to 18.
</P>
<P>
The first three economic conferences were separately convened
in the Moroccan city of Casablanca in 1994, in the Jordanian
capital of Amman in 1995 and the Egyptian capital of Cairo in
1996.
</P>
<P>
Qatar hopes to invite 2,500 delegates, including Israeli
businessmen, to the conference and it will propose some 30
projects requiring investment of 3 billion U.S. dollars during the
conference.
</P>
<P>
The existing law prohibits foreigners from holding more than
49 percent of stakes in a Qatari project or firm.
</P>
<P>
Kamal said the amended law would serve as an incentive for
foreign companies to invest more in the country and he asked
Qatari businessmen to scout out foreign partners with fund and
technical know-how to set up medium and small projects in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
