<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Condemns Anti-Islam Poster Found In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- In an effort to dampen a
possible religious flareup, Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu today condemned the anti-Islamic leaflet that appeared
in Hebron over the weekend, reported the state-run Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
The leaflet showed Mohammed as a pig writing in the
Koran. The provocative drawing appeared at more than 20
Palestinian stores near the Jewish enclave of Beit Hadassah in
downtown Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah Hassouneh, 60, who owns one of the shops, said: "I
came out at 7 o'clock in the morning, only to find the drawing
posted on my shop's door. It is a criminal act and humiliating
to the Islamic religion."
</P>
<P>
"They do not have a principle and even their religion does not
permit such violations against other religions," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a phone call to Hebron Mayor Mustafa Natshe, Netanyahu
described the incident as very grave. He said that the drawing
contradicts the respect which the Jewish people hold for Islam
and other religions.
</P>
<P>
Natshe promised to convey his remarks to the Palestinian
residents in the city.
</P>
<P>
Police said that a 25-year-old Jewish woman from Jerusalem,
detained for stoning a vehicle near the Machpela Cave in Hebron,
is suspected of distributing and posting the posters outside
Palestinian stores.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish settlers in Hebron also issued a statement
condemning the leaflets. But Palestinian residents believe that
the settlers have helped the woman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
