<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNA: Egypt, Among Only Mediators in Place Now </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb
Erekat today hailed the sustained Egyptian efforts to salvage the
faltering Mideast peace process but deplored the absence of other
mediators.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview given this morning with the Egyptian
Voice of Arab radio from Jerusalem, Erekat said that the Egyptian
efforts have now become "the only ones made to patch up the
staggering peace process."
</P>
<P>
He characterized the Egyptian initiative at this crux as
seeking to remove reasons behind the current quagmire of the
Mideast peacemaking because of Israel's ground-breaking for a
Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem in March.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Middle East News Agency (MENA) said recently that
Egyptian presidential political advisor Osama el-Baz will set out
for Tel Aviv early this week on a new round of shuttle tour in a
bid to narrow the gap between Israel and the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian and U.S. mediations have failed to bring the two
sides back to the negotiating table after a three-month freeze in
contacts while violence flared up anew in the occupied Palestinian
territories.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian public became furious as the U.S. Senate's
appropriation subcommittee decided ten days ago to withdraw aid
from Egypt on the grounds that it pursued what it called an
obstructionist policy in the regional peace-making.
</P>
<P>
The subcommittee removed allocations for Egypt totalling 2.1
billion U.S. dollars, while maintaining Israel's 3 billion
dollars grant and creating a 250-million-dollar fund for Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has made it clear that it will not succumb to pressure
by foregin powers through aid. Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said
the decision would not affect Egypt's commitment to the peace
process and its efforts to salvage it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
