<P>
CAIRO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary-General
Esmat Abdel Meguid said today that Libya has readily accepted
proposals by the Arab League and the Organization of African Unity
(OAU) to solve the Lockerbie crisis.
</P>
<P>
The AL and the OAU has proposed that the two Libyans, suspected
of involvement in the bombing of a Pan AM airliner over Lockerbie,
Scotland, in 1988, which killed 270 people, be tried by a justice
from Scotland in a third country other than in Britain and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian MENA news agency quoted the AL cheif as saying
that he had asked U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to persuade
the countries concerned with the Lockerbie crisis to accept the
proposals which he described as "fair" solutions to ending the
dispute.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed sanctions against Tripoli for its refusal to
hand over the two Libyans to Britain and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Libyan leader Mummar Gaddafi has suggested the two be tried
anywhere else than in the U.S. and Britain.
</P>
<P>
"Libya will not hand over the suspects (to Britain or the U.S.)
for fear that they will not stand a fair trial there, but it is
ready to hand over them to a neutral court," Meguid said.
</P>
<P>
He pledged strenuous Arab efforts to settle the crisis in order
to ease the suffering of the Libyan people as a result of the
five-year-old embargo.
</P>
<P>
Both the OAU and Al have been calling for a prompt lift of
international sanctions against Libya over the Lockerbie crisis
and aired support for Tripoli's overtures to settle the dispute.
</P>
<P>
The Libya-West crisis was discussed for the first time early
this month at the Harare OAU summit which called for lifting the
sanctions and taking temporary measures to help ease the
sufferings of the Libyan people.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, during his two-day visit to
the Libyan coastal city of Tobruk on June 12-13, also denounced
the U.N.-imposed ban on Libya and urged an immediate removal of
it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
