<HEADLINE> UNHCR to Repatriate Congo Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations High
Commission for Refugees (UNHCR) sub-office in Kigoma, Western
Tanzania, will start repatriating five thousand refugees in the
Republic of Congo back to their homes, local press reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR spokesman, Yasin Hamid, told reporters in the town
of Kigoma on Saturday that 300 refugees will be transported by
boat starting from Monday evening and are scheduled to arrive at
Karundu harbour, Ruvira, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The group will be received by UNHCR and the government
officials at Ruvira in the Democratic Republic of Congo, Hamid
added.
</P>
<P>
Hamid said the decision to repatriate the 5,000 refugees from
Kigoma region followed their own choices.
</P>
<P>
"They voluntarily signed forms expressing their wish to be
repatriated," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hamid said even before this decision was reached,
some refugees from the two refugee camps have been leaving the
camps for home, with the assistance of the UNHCR.
</P>
<P>
Accoring to a report, 93,809 refugees from the Congo
Democratic Republic are currently staying in the Kigoma region.
</P>
</TEXT>
