<HEADLINE> Return of Hong Kong, Hottest News for Beijing Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Newspaper bulletins on Beijing
streets have attracted more passers-by these days, as the return
of Hong Kong to the motherland on July 1 approaches.
</P>
<P>
In front of more than 100 newspaper bulletins near the city's
major structures, people are reading the People's Daily, Xinhua
Daily Telegraph and other major Beijing-based newspapers to search
for stories about the return of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"It is a major event that concerns the entire nation," said Li
Lianju, a retired worker, who was carefully reading today's
People's Daily from a bulletin on Western Chang'an Avenue.
</P>
<P>
Li Zhao'e, a shop-assistant at Wangfujing Department Store,
joined the people reading newspapers from a bulletin in front of
the store, in her lunch time. "Nothing interests me more than the
return of Hong Kong," she said, eating a hamburger for lunch.
</P>
<P>
People who come to subscribe newspapers have also increased
these days. According to an employee of the Liubukou Post Office,
which is located opposite to the State Council and other central
Party and government organizations in Zhongnanhai, the number of
subscribers in his office has increased by a hundreds in a day.
</P>
<P>
Ma Zhenyu, a newspaper collector in Beijing, subscribed more
than 90 kinds of newspapers for his colleagues living outside
Beijing. "The return of Hong Kong provides a good opportunity for
newspaper collection on special subjects." he said. 
</P>
