<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey: One Third of Israeli University Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 29 (Xinhua) -- One-third of Israeli university
students have tried drugs some time in their lives, and 21 percent
of them did so during the past year, local English-language
newspaper The Jerusalem Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed in a new survey released last week on drug
use among young people to coincide with the World Anti-Drug Day,
which was marked Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Shlomo Gal, director of the Anti-Drug
Authority, as saying that the survey "sets off alarm bells." "If
something drastic isn't done in education and prevention, we'll
find ourselves facing a national social problem with many
implications," he said.
</P>
<P>
Gal said that an additional cause for worry is that drug use
begins at younger ages, adding that "this behavior can be found
today even among children 10 or 12. "
</P>
<P>
He warned against differentiating between "soft drugs"
(hashish and marijuana) and "hard drugs" (cocaine and heroin),
as young people think there is nothing wrong with the former and
then they "graduate" to the latter.
</P>
<P>
Gal called on parents to get more involvement in the issue and
look for suspicious signs of drug use. "They must discuss the
dangers of drugs with their children," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
