<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pride of Chinese: Interview with Henry Fok Ying-Tung (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Just think of the feeling of a
Hong Kong resident who knew that he was a Chinese but could not
identify him as a Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Only with the understanding of such an experience of many Hong
Kong residents can people really come to know the tremendous
inspiration and pride the upcoming return of Hong Kong to China
has brought to the Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
"When Hong Kong people went abroad, they couldn't identify
themselves as Chinese and were unwilling to identify themselves as
British, they could only write 'stateless' on the entry form,"
said Henry Fok Ying-tung, an influential businessman in Hong Kong
and vice chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC).
</P>
<P>
"After Hong Kong's return on July 1, Hong Kong compatriots will
become dignified Chinese with tremendous pride," he told reporters
recently in his hometown of Nansha, Panyu County, Guangdong
Province.
</P>
<P>
Fok, 74, who was born and grew up in Hong Kong, witnessed the
period of history when China was invaded and the Chinese people
were humiliated. Fifty-eight years ago, the Japanese aggressors
occupied large areas of Chinese territory.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen-year-old Fok changed his name from "Fok Haojian" to his
present name "Fok Ying-tung," implying the hope that one day the
Chinese nation could "stand as a strong nation in the East of the
world."
</P>
<P>
With the passage of several decades, and the Chinese nation has
eventually found a way to make itself strong which is suited to
its realities. The once-sleeping lion now stands like a giant in
the East.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong will return to the motherland soon. This indicates
that the Chinese nation has become strong. Hong Kong's smooth
return fully demonstrates that only when our motherland becomes
strong and prosperous, can we Chinese people wipe out a national
disgrace of more than 100 years," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970629.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pride of Chinese: Interview with Henry Fok Ying-Tung (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When he returned to his hometown Panyu 18 years ago, he was
struck by poverty and backwardness there. "I wanted to make a
phone call, and but couldn't get through for a long time. I asked
someone to ride a bike to meet the person, and he got there and
yet I still did not get through for my call."
</P>
<P>
Panyu was a poor small town then and Nansha was a bleak place
with few restaurants. "Not only Panyu, but the whole of the
country was poor then. Once I stayed in the interior areas for 49
days, and simply couldn't make a long-distance call to my family,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Everyone can see clearly what China looks like today. The
facts are there," he said. On top of the Nansha Mountain, pointing
to the Humen Bridge, factories, residential buildings and a steady
stream of moving vehicles, he said, "This (Nansha) is only a small
town of Panyu. One can imagine what tremendous changes have taken
in China in recent years. But for the policy of the reform and
opening up, China could not have become what it is today."
</P>
<P>
In his view, only sustained development in China's inland areas
can ensure the smooth transition of Hong Kong. "As a matter of
fact, the process of Hong Kong's return has proceeded
simultaneously with the reform and opening up in the inland
areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that every phase of Hong Kong's return process -- from
the Sino-British negotiations in the early 1980s, the signing of
the Sino-British Joint Declaration, the drafting of the Basic Law,
to the establishment of the Preparatory Committee and the
formation of the Government of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region -- was accompanied by the increase in
China's national strength, the deepening of the reform and the
opening wider to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
"Without the steady increase in the national strength, the Hong
Kong issue could not have been solved so smoothly, and Hong Kong
would not have enjoyed the stability and prosperity as it does
today," Fok pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"The reform and opening up are the correct choice made by the
Chinese people after decades of exploration. Practice has proven
that this is the road that will enable China to become strong and
the Chinese people to achieve prosperity. In this sense, the
policy of the reform and opening up will never change," he said.
</P>
<P>
"So long as China advances along this road, its national
strength will become increasingly stronger and Hong Kong will
become increasingly prosperous, and the principle of 'one country,
two systems' will certainly succeed," he said.
</P>
<P>
"As a Chinese, I feel proud and dignified," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
