<HEADLINE> Western Values Blasted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Vice-President Simon
Muzenda on Saturday described young Zimbabweans who despise their
own music and traditions as "a terrible shame and disgrace".
</P>
<P>
In a statement presented by Cephas Msipa, minister of state in
the president's office at this year's Arts Festival held at the
University of Zimbabwe (UZ), Muzenda said Zimbabweans should
devote their time and energy to studying traditional music and
dances in order to preserve their indigenous cultural values.
</P>
<P>
"I regard it a terrible shame and disgrace that, some of our
young people seem bent on throwing anything that is African,
including our languages, preferring to imitate western values
which can never be ours even in a million years," said Muzenda.
</P>
<P>
He added that it was encouraging to know that some young
people were seriously pursuing and studying different types of
Zimbabwean music and dances.
</P>
<P>
The UZ Arts Festival was characterised by traditional African
music, dance, drama, poetry performed by students from the
capital. 
</P>
