<HEADLINE> Malaysia Detects 38 New Drug Addicts Daily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Thirty-eight new drug addicts
were detected daily with the majority of them aged between 16 and
34, showing the seriousness of the situation, Malaysian National
Association Against Drug Abuse vice-president Lee Lam Thye said
today.
</P>
<P>
In view of the seriousness of the situation, the community and
individuals must seriously renew their commitment to tackle the
malaise, he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
A more effective approach and strategy from all parties
including government agencies, non-governmental organizations,
voluntary and religious organizations as well as political parties
must be implemented immediately, Lee said, adding efforts to curb
drug addiction problem required close cooperation from all strata
of society as it was not an easy task.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government spent 550 million ringgit (about 220
million U.S. dollars) to deal with the country's drugs scourge
between 1984 and 1996 but the menace had yet to be wiped out
completely.
</P>
<P>
The amount was spent particularly for treatment and
rehabilitation programs in drug rehabilitation centers, prisons
and other educational programs, according to Lee.
</P>
<P>
Prisons Department director-general Zaman Khan said recently
that the government spent 750,000 ringgit (about 300,000 U.S.
dollars) a day for the 15,000 addicts in rehabilitation centers
and another 10,000 under the charge of the prison authorities
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
Last year, a total of 13,846 new drug addicts were detected in
Malaysia and the number of drug addicts in the country now stands
at some 200,000, Lee disclosed earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
