<HEADLINE> Holyfield Retains WBA Heavyweight Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Evander Holyfield retained the
WBA heavyweight championship Saturday night in Las Vegas as Mike
Tyson was disqualified for biting his opponent's ears after the
third round.
</P>
<P>
After the bout, Tyson complained to referee Mills Lane and then
charged across the ring to Holyfield. Tyson hit a police officer
before being pulled away.
</P>
<P>
Tyson's 30 million U.S. dollars purse was being withheld
pending a hearing before the Nevada Athletic Commission, according
Marc Ratner, executive director of the commission.
</P>
<P>
Holyfield took advantage in the first two rounds while Tyson
was winning the third. With 40 seconds remaining, Holyfield
suddenly jumped up and run away in angry with a bleeding right ear.
</P>
<P>
The fight suspended four minutes and Tyson bit Holyfield on the
left ear. Both men then exchanged punches that didn't connect.
</P>
<P>
After the round ended, Lane disqualified Tyson and explained
that his decision was not due to the bleeding but due to the foul.
</P>
<P>
Lane was named referee Friday after Mitch Halpern voluntarily
withdrew. John Horne and Roy Holloway, Tyson's managers, had
protested that Halpern, the referee of the first fight on November
9, 1996, wouldn't treat him fairly.
</P>
<P>
Tyson began the fight cautiously and was cut at the corner of
the right eye in the second round. Lane ruled it as an accidental
head butt, which made Tyson extremely angry.
</P>
<P>
The third round became wild and crazy. Early in the round,
Tyson landed several short punches to the head that moved
Holyfield back and took the advantage when he bit Holyfield on the
ear.
</P>
<P>
With the victory, Holyfield earned at least 35 million
U.S. dollars and improved his record to 34-3 with 24
knockouts. Tyson dropped to 45 wins, three defeats with 39
konckouts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
