<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Ready for Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong is ready for the
handover ceremony to be held at the midnight of June 30 in the
Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition Center (CEC).
Decoration of functional halls in the CEC, security measures
inside and around it, telecom facilities serving the ceremony and
arrangements of transport to and from the CEC have basically been
completed, according to the Handover Ceremony Coordination Office.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong police have sealed off traffic to the CEC
extension, where the handover ceremony will be held, from June 25
and are making a blanket security check-up around it. Only people
having special passes can enter the extension. The police have
also announced restricted areas near the CEC during the period of
the handover and other activities.
</P>
<P>
British Prince of Wales, who will represent the Queen to attend
the handover ceremony, arrived in Hong Kong yesterday afternoon.
Dignitaries from other countries who will attend the grand
ceremony have also arrived, and others are expected to come today
or tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Local telecom, power and mass transit departments have
announced special service arrangements to ensure the smooth going
of the handover ceremony and the inauguration ceremony for the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
Between June 29 and July 2, Hong Kong Telecom will provide free
transmission, to all parts of the world, programs of celebration
organized by the Committee for Activities to Mark Hong Kong's
Return to the Motherland by Various Sectors in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Utility companies in Hong Kong have made cooperative
arrangements with their counterparts in south China's Guangdong
Province on the provision of ample power supply during the
handover period.
</P>
<P>
The Mass Transit Railway will provide all-night services on
June 30. Thirty bus lines will extend service hours between June
30 and July 1.
</P>
<P>
The legislative, judicial and administrative framework of the
HKSAR has taken shape and is ready for functioning on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The Royal Yacht, Britannia, which is to take the last governor
Christ Patten from Hong Kong, has arrived and is moored at the
Victoria Harbor.
</P>
<P>
Advance troops of the Chinese People's Liberation Army will
march into Hong Kong from 09:00 pm June 30 for deployment so that
they can take up Hong Kong's defense responsibility at zero hour
of July 1.
</P>
<P>
In about one month from mid June, people of all walks of life
in Hong Kong will have more than 400 celebration programs
including book, painting, stamp and flower shows, gala balls,
theatrical, musical and acrobatic performances, competitions,
receptions, float parades and fireworks shows.
</P>
<P>
All major buildings on Hong Kong Island and in Kowloon and the
"New Territories" have been decorated with the regional flag and
regional emblem of the HKSAR as well as lantern designs. Cars and
light buses in the streets fly the regional flag.
</P>
<P>
At night, Hong Kong Island and Kowloon are illuminated as
bright as day. In Nathan Street in Kowloon, a 3.5-kilometer-long
dragon delineated with neon lights was lit up at 8:37 pm yesterday
and will be kept illuminated in the following nights.  
</P>
</TEXT>
