<HEADLINE> Iran Ready to Sign Security Pacts with Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Iran is ready to sign security and
defense pacts with its southern Arab neighbors in a bid to
promote security in the region, a senior Iranian military
official was quoted today as saying.
</P>
<P>
Major-General Mohsen Rezaie, Commander of the Islamic
Revolution Guard Corps (IRGC), made the remarks in an interview
carried in today's English daily Kayhan International.
</P>
<P>
The major-general also warned that any U.S. military
adventurism against Iran would be crushed. He called on foreign
military forces in the Persian Gulf to get out of the region.
</P>
<P>
Rezaie is expected to replace current Defense Minister
Mohammad Forouzandeh in the new government headed by Mohammad
Khatami, who won a landslide victory in the 7th presidential
election on May 23.
</P>
<P>
"We need security because we don't want our vital interests
be jeopardized. We have proved our good intentions. Now, we are
ready to sign security and defense pacts with all our Arab
neighbors in the Persian Gulf region," Rezaie said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.N. Security Council Resolution 598 also
calls for security cooperation among the Persian Gulf
states. "Iran has no expansionist desire and we want peaceful
coexistence with our neighbors," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Local observers believe that Iran has taken a bold gesture by
offering to sign security and defense pacts with its southern
Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Election of moderate intellectual Mohammad Khatami as
president has strengthened Iran's desire to promote confidence
building and rapprochement between Iran and Arab countries in
the region, they said.
</P>
<P>
Rezaie attacked the United States for seeking to destabilize
the region, saying that "they want to keep the regional states
under pressure and threats."
</P>
<P>
However, he sent a message to Americans: "Let me send a clear
message to the Americans: the Persian Gulf is our region. They
have to leave our region. We have vital interests in the Persian
Gulf and we are going to defend interests."
</P>
<P>
On the issue of possible military confrontation between Iran
and the United States, he said, Iran will never start any
war. But if Americans one day decide to attack us, then they
will have committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
"We will turn the region into a slaughterhouse for them. There
is no place better than the Persian Gulf to destroy Americans'
might," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that "there is a possibility that Israelis may
provoke America to seek adventurism in the region."
</P>
<P>
"In that case, they may be a good starter but the end of such
a war will not be in America's hands. The American people should
not let their children be killed in a war incited by Israel," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Rezaie noted that the presence of foreign powers, especially
U.S. forces, in the Persian Gulf, is tantamount to an aggression
against the region. "It is against international norms and it
creates instability in this region." he said.
</P>
<P>
"Iran is committed to protect security in the Persian Gulf
and is trying with patience to get foreign forces out of this
region," he added.
</P>
<P>
The general also criticized U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen for his defense of U.S. presence in the region. "The
Americans have for the first time announced that they would
remain in the region as long as (Iraqi President) Saddam Hussein
is in power in Iraq," he said, adding that "this shows they have
retreated one step back since they had never given any time limit
for their withdrawal before."
</P>
<P>
On Iran's defense capability, he said, Iran is now producing
advanced anti-tank rockets as well as short-range and medium-
range missiles.
</P>
<P>
But, he added, "there is no limitation in producing our
defense requirements within the international rules."
</P>
<P>
"I do confirm that we are seeking to expand our defense
capability but we have no desire to acquire banned weapons such
as nuclear bombs and chemical weapons." 
</P>
</TEXT>
