<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The much-talked by-poll in
Manikganj, dozens miles away from Bangladesh's capital Dhaka, is
expected to be held tomorrow while the main rivals warned each
other against bid to rig the election.
</P>
<P>
The Manikganj-3 seat was vacated after the death of the main
opposition Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) lawmaker Nizamuddin
Khan in March this year.
</P>
<P>
Though six candidates are in the race, the main contest is
between the nominees of the ruling Awami (people's) League, the
BNP and the third largest Jatiya (national) Party led by former
President H.M. Ershad.
</P>
<P>
The BNP, though boycotted two earlier by-elections on the pleas
of partisan role of the Election Commission, is contesting this
by-election. But they have warned of a movement to topple the
government if it tries to rig the by-election.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina on Saturday also warned
that the government will not allow anyone to rig the polls.
"Nobody can play with the voting rights of the people," she said,
indicating that the BNP might have the ill motive.
</P>
<P>
The voting will start at 8 am (local time) in 404 centers and
continue till 4 p.m. (local time) without break amidst adequate
security, said the Election Commission in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The commission has given directive to the concerned authorities
to hold the election peacefully and properly while an electoral
committee has been formed to investigate any complaint of
irregularities or violation of code of conduct.  
</P>
