<HEADLINE> Alcoholism on Rise Among Singapore Women: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Alcoholism may be on the rise
among Singapore women because of changing lifestyles, growing
affluence and stress, the Sunday edition of the Straits Times,
said in a report today.
</P>
<P>
The number of women with alcohol problems is growing, though
only a few are seeking treatment, the report quoted psychiatrists
and psychologists as saying.
</P>
<P>
Seven professionals told the Sunday Times that they now see
more women with alcohol problems, despite the lack of
comprehensive statistics. They said they each have two to three
among their current patients, compared with perhaps one or none
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
They said they believe there are more out there who have not
come forward because they are too ashamed.
</P>
<P>
Changing lifestyles and growing affluence may explain why more
women are turning to drink, they said. "Alcohol consumption and
disposable income have gone up. It's more acceptable now for women
to drink. They have ladies' nights at most discos, and pubs are no
longer seen as seedy," one explained.
</P>
<P>
One psychologist in private practice said that the change in
women's roles has put many women under stress. "Unable to cope
with new pressures of family and work, they turn to alcohol as an
escape," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
