<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Power of Final Adjudication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Before July 1, 1997, under
British colonial rule, Hong Kong has adopted British laws and the
British Legal system. Lawsuits in different categories and classes
are routed to the magistrates' courts, the district courts and the
High Court.
</P>
<P>
However, Hong Kong has never had the power of final
adjudication, with its court of final appeal in the British Privy
Council.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR) has stipulated that after Hong Kong returns to China on
July 1, 1997, the Hong Kong SAR will be vested with the power of
final adjudication except for cases concerning the territorial
integrity of the state, national defense and foreign affairs, and
the relationship between the central authorities and the Hong Kong
SAR.
</P>
<P>
This is intended to ensure that the HKSAR enjoy a high degree
of autonomy and have full and independent judicial power.
</P>
<P>
Lawsuits within the Hong Kong SAR may be subject to the final
adjudication by the Court of Final Appeal of the SAR, the Basic
Law stipulates.
</P>
<P>
It also stipulates that the Chief Justice of the Court of Final
Appeal of the HKSAR must be Chinese citizens who are permanent
residents of the region with no right of abode in any foreign
country.
</P>
<P>
In the appointment or removal of judges of the Court of Final
Appeal and the Chief Justice of the High Court, the Chief
Executive of the HKSAR must, in addition to going through
procedures stipulated in the Basic Law, obtain the endorsement of
the Legislative Council and report such appointment or removal to
the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress for
record. 
</P>
</TEXT>
