<DOCNO> XIE19970629.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronicle of HK's Major Historical Events (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On March 31, 1993: as the British side adopted an uncooperative
attitude on the issue of Hong Kong, the First Session of the
Eighth NPC adopted the decision that authorized the NPC Standing
Committee to establish a preliminary working body of the
Preparatory Committee for the HKSAR. On July 2, the Standing
Committee of the Eighth NPC adopted the decision to establish the
Preliminary Working Committee of the Preparatory Committee for the
HKSAR. The preliminary working committee was officially
established on July 16. Its main duties included all kinds of
preparatory work for China's resumption of the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong in 1997 and for Hong Kong's smooth
transition.
</P>
<P>
From April to November in 1993: representatives of the Chinese
and British governments held 17 rounds of talks concerning the
arrangements for the 1994/1995 election. During the 17th round,
the British side unilaterally announced the suspension of the
talks.
</P>
<P>
On January 26, 1996: the Preparatory Committee for the HKSAR
was established. It consisted of 150 members, of whom 94, or 63
percent, came from Hong Kong. The committee was in charge of the
preparatory work for the establishment of the SAR. As the British
side unilaterally pursued its "political reform package," the
existing Legislative Council of Hong Kong could not become the
first Legislative Council of the HKSAR. To ensure the smooth
transition and avoid a legal vacuum, the Preparatory Committee
decided to form a Provisional Legislative Council for the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
On November 2, 1996: the Preparatory Committee elected the
Selection Committee for the first HKSAR government. The Selection
Committee was in charge of selecting the first Chief Executive and
the Provisional Legislative Council of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
On December 11, 1996: the Selection Committee elected Tung Chee
Hwa as the first Chief Executive of the HKSAR; on December 16, the
11th Plenary Meeting of the State Council approved the
appointment, and Premier Li Peng signed the No. 207 State Council
Decree that appointed Tung Chee Hwa as the first Chief Executive
of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
On December 21, 1996: in Shenzhen, the Selection Committee
elected 60 members of the Provisional Legislative Council of the
HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
On January 24, 1997: Tung Chee Hwa announced the list of the
members of the first Executive Council of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
On February 20, 1997: the 23 principal officials of the HKSAR
government nominated by Tung were appointed by the State Council.
</P>
<P>
On May 20, 1997: according to the recommendation by the
Judiciary Recommendation Committee, Tung agreed to appoint Li
Kwok-nang Chief Justice of the HKSAR Court of Final Appeal. The
appointment will take effect on July 1.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970629.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Provisional Legislative Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- Due to the sabotage by the
British side, the "through-train" arrangement, which means that
members of Hong Kong's last Legislative Council may become, upon
confirm ation by the Preparatory Committee for the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), members of the first
Legislative Council of the HKSAR, has been derailed.
</P>
<P>
Since the last Legislative Council of the British Hong Kong
authorities cannot continue to operate after July 1, 1997, and it
is also impossible to form the first Legislative Council of the
HKSAR on July 1 or soon after that, there will be a temporary
legislative vacuum after the founding of the HKSAR if no measure
is taken.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there will be many affairs that require the
participation of the legislature after the Hong Kong SAR is
established, particularly such as the formulation of new laws for
the transfer of power. Therefore, there must be a temporary body
to exercise the power of the first HKSAR Legislative Council prior
to its formation.
</P>
<P>
On April 4, 1990, the National People's Congress, China's
legislature, adopted a "Decision on the Method for the Formation
of the First Government and the First Legislative Council of the
HKSAR", which granted the HKSAR Preparatory Committee the power to
"take charge of relevant affairs relating to the preparations for
the establishment of the HKSAR".
</P>
<P>
In March of 1996, the HKSAR Preparatory Committee adopted a
"Decision on the Establishment of the HKSAR Provisional
Legislative Council (PLC)" at its second plenary session.
</P>
<P>
On December 21, 1996, a Selection Committee for the First HKSAR
Government, which was composed of 400 permanent residents of Hong
Kong, held its fourth plenary session in Shenzhen and elected
through secret ballot the 60-member PLC of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The major functions of the PLC include formulating laws that
are urgently-needed and indispensable in the early days of the
HKSAR government, amending some laws that required to be revised
before continuing to be applicable, and declaring the termination
of several laws that have no necessities to be preserved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970629.0114 </DOCNO>
