<HEADLINE> Brazilian Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
-- The gross domestic product (GDP) is expected to grow 4.3
percent this year as against last year's 3.0 percent, a study from
the Applied Economic Research Institute (IPEA) showed.
</P>
<P>
The study said that GDP rose 5.6 percent in the year ending
June this year, 0.8 percent higher than the prediction made in May.
</P>
<P>
The GDP growth projection for the third quarter rose from 3.3
percent to 4.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
-- The accumulated inflation reached 68.98 percent since the
"Plan Real" went in force in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilian Geography and Statistics Institute (IBGE) said
the country's inflation was 900 percent in 1994 and reduced to 22
percent in 1995 and to 5.87 in the year ending in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
The steepest price rise was a 285 percent jump for housing,
followed by communications, personal service, public
transportation, education, medical service, fish and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
-- Total grain production in 1997 will reach 78.34 million
tons, a 4.68 percent increase over the 72.98-million-ton output in
1996.
</P>
<P>
The IBGE reported that production in the state of Rondonia will
account for 89.4 percent of the total estimate. 
</P>
