<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Customs Chief on Future Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 29 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Customs will
further improve its efficiency and raise service standards after
July 1 when China resumes the exercise of sovereignty over Hong
Kong, said Lawrence Li Shu-fai, commissioner of Customs and Excise
of Hong Kong, in an interview with Xinhua.
The interview happened to be on the same day when the Hong Kong
Customs made public its new insignia to be used from July 1 when
Hong Kong returns to China.
</P>
<P>
On the new insignia, the crown has been replaced by a bauhinia,
a flower representing Hong Kong. Otherwise, the insignia features
a sword and a key crossing each other.
Pointing at the sword and key, Li said they represent law
enforcement and the collection of duties.
</P>
<P>
"Mind you, this is a Chinese sword, a symbol of high authority,
that gives the bearer discretionary powers," he said.
</P>
<P>
A seasoned customs officer, the 53-year-old Li became the first
Chinese commissioner of customs and excise of Hong Kong when he
was appointed to lead the 4,300-strong customs force in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
Li will serve at his present post for the future Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region.
He said he was aware of his heavy responsibilities as
commissioner of customs.
</P>
<P>
The Customs is an important government department in Hong Kong,
he said. Aside from ensuring internal security and duty
collection, the customs cracks down on illegal activities such as
smuggling, drug trafficking and infringement of intellectual
property rights.
"Whether or not the Customs does a good job has a bearing on Hong
Kong's image in the international community as well as on its own
economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that, with rapid economic expansion in Hong Kong, the
Customs is facing new challenges and that people's expectations of
the Customs are rising.
</P>
<P>
Main tasks for the Customs at present, he said, range from
cracking down on drug trafficking and smuggling, protection of
intellectual property rights, tariff collection, management of
export quotas, safety standards for consumer goods, to control of
the import and export of contrabands such as goods that cause
serious pollution, explosives, and protected plants and animals.
</P>
<P>
Specific plans include the construction of a new customs
building in two or three years, improvement of its computer
network as well as its administrative structure.
"The Customs will do its best to further improve work efficiency
and raise service standards," he said.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner expects closer cooperation with his
counterparts in inland areas of China, especially the customs in
neighboring Guangdong province. Over the past 15 years, the heads
of Hong Kong and Guangdong customs have held annual meetings and
liaison officers of the two customs meet once every six weeks, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970629.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PICC Group to Reform Pay, Promotion Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- China's largest insurance
underwriter, the People's Insurance Co of China (PICC), will
reform its operations to maintain its leading status in domestic
market.
</P>
<P>
A senior manager of PICC said the group would change its
employment, promotion and pay systems in order to "meet the
challenges from domestic and overseas counterparts".
</P>
<P>
The iron rice-bowl system, which guarantees lifelong
employment, should be broken. Instead, the industry should
employment a contractual employment system, under which employees
can be fired if they do not fulfill their work requirements, said
PICC Group Vice President Wu Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
The "iron chair" system, which secures an official's position
after he or she is promoted, would be abolished, Wu was quoted
today by China Daily's "Business Weekly" as saying.
</P>
<P>
The group headquarters is planning to appoint heads for seven
departments through public selection, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
The group would link employees' income with performance, and
senior officials of the group are no exception, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We will make more efforts in transforming operations to meet
the challenges from our domestic and overseas counterparts," he
said.
</P>
<P>
PICC Group, which owns life, property and reinsurance
subsidiaries, is being rivaled by some 20 domestic insurance
companies and more and more foreign insurers that are striving to
crack China's market.  
</P>
