<DOCNO> XIE19970629.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Berths for China's Largest Coal Terminal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINHUANGDAO, June 29 (Xinhua) -- A new terminal at Qinhuangdao
port on Bohai Bay in north China will start trial operation on
July 1, port authorities say.
</P>
<P>
The terminal has three berths: one for 100,000-ton vessels and
two for 35,000-ton. It adds 30 million tons to the port's annual
coal handling capacity, raising the total capacity to about 127
million tons annually.
</P>
<P>
Qinhuangdao is now the second port in China with a yearly
capacity surpassing 100 million tons, and is considered the
largest coal terminal in the world. Last year it handled 83.1
million tons of cargo, 65.5 million tons of which was coal.
</P>
<P>
A fourth phase of construction began in April 1993. The
terminal has handled a total of 1.88 million tons of coal while
installing and testing equipment.
</P>
<P>
Approximately 1.68 billion yuan has been spent on the project,
including 10.34 billion yen from a Japanese government loan. The
Mitsubishi company of Japan won a bid to supply the main equipment.
</P>
<P>
North China produces most of the coal used in the South. A
large part of it is transported by ship, and Qinhuangdao handles
nearly 70 percent of the south-bound coal carriers.
</P>
<P>
The phase four project was to make use of a railway built
earlier, between Qinhuangdao and Datong in Shanxi Province, the
largest coal production base in China. The 653-kilometer
Datong-Qinhuangdao line is solely for coal transport and is
capable of handling 100 million tons a year.
</P>
<P>
The new coal terminal is equipped with advanced dock
facilities. It is run by the Seventh Stevedore Company, which was
established in May 1996 and now has 659 employees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970629.0128 </DOCNO>
