<HEADLINE> 47 Climbers Scale Mt. Qomolangma from Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 28 (Xinhua) -- A total of 47 climbers have
scaled from Nepal the 8848-meter high Mt. Qomolangma, the highest
peak of the world, during the first three months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 47, 25 are Nepalese nationals, the rest are from
Russia, the United States, Iceland, Canada, Indonesia, Australia,
Mexico, New Zealand, Finland and Malaysia, said the Nepali
Ministry of Tourism and Civil Aviation.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian nationals reached the top of Mt. Qomolangma for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 10 climbers from Australia, South Korea, Japan and
Nepal have scaled the 8167-meter high Mt. Dhaulagiri during the
spring season of mountaineering which lasted from March 1, 1997
until May 31, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Out of the seven expeditions who were permitted to climb the
8586-meter high Mt. Kanchenjunga, only one climber from the United
States succeeded.
</P>
<P>
And 12 climbers from Russia, Britain, France, Mexico and Italy
reached the top of 8516-meter high Mt. Lhotse.
</P>
<P>
The 8463-meter high Mt. Makalu also saw five Russians on its
top.
</P>
<P>
Seven mountaineers--three Russians, one British and three
Nepalese--lost their lives during the season, the Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 48 expeditions were permitted to climb different
peaks of Nepal during this season.  
</P>
</TEXT>
