<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Communications Ministry Shipping Regulations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 29 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Communications
recently issued a circular on shipping services between the
country's inland areas and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
It says that after the return of Hong Kong, shipping companies
and ships registered in the inland areas will still be operating
under current regulations when they are engaged in marine
transportation between Hong Kong and ports on the mainland that
are open to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Shipping companies and ships registered in Hong Kong will be
allowed to engage in marine transportation between Hong Kong and
ports on the mainland that are open to the outside world. But they
must get approval from the Communications Ministry in accordance
with the relevant international regulation when engaged in either
passenger or cargo transport.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-registered ships cannot engage in either passenger or
cargo transport between Hong Kong and ports on the mainland open
to foreign ships without approval from the Communications Ministry.
</P>
<P>
After July 1, ships registered in Hong Kong or on the mainland
cannot hoist a flag on the mainmast when entering a port on the
mainland or Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
When a ship registered in Hong Kong enters a mainland port, the
Chinese national flag and the Hong Kong regional flag are to be
flown from the stern of the ship.
</P>
<P>
When a ship registered on the mainland enters a Hong Kong port,
the national flag is to be flown from the stern.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-registered ships that have gotten approval from the
Communications Ministry to engage in shipping between the mainland
and Hong Kong are to fly the Chinese flag and the Hong Kong
regional flag from the mainmast when entering a Hong Kong port.
</P>
<P>
Sources also say that some departments are working on
administrative methods for shipping services between the mainland
and Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
