<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ivanisevic Knocked out of Wimbledon Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WIMBLEDON, June 28 (Xinhua) -- Croatian veteran star Goran
Ivanisevic was knocked out of the on-going Wimbledon tennis
championships Saturday after losing a five-set battle to young
Swedish player Magnus Norman.
</P>
<P>
Norman, beat world number one Pete Sampras at the recent French
Open, put up an inspiring fighting form at the All England Law
Tennis Club and refused to make any concessions to the world's
most powerful server.
</P>
<P>
Ivanisevic, the second seed and twice a losing finalist, set a
record for the number of aces in a match, but at the crucial final
set the temperamental player lost his patience the conceded a
remarkable 3-6 6-2 6-7 6-4 12-14 defeat.
</P>
<P>
Although the 21-year-old Swede sailed into the third round, his
hear problem, which nearly forced him to abandon Saturday's match,
would cast a long shadow upon his future Wimbledon battles ahead.
</P>
<P>
Norman will now consult his doctor in Sweden to discuss how
serious a risk he would be taking by continuing in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the match, Norman told reporters: "Last time it
happened to me it lasted for 40 minutes, today it was just for 30
seconds. I am going to phone my doctor in Sweden and we're going
to take the decision."
</P>
<P>
Tenth seed Carlos Moya of Spain was another major casualty on
Saturday. The rising young tennis star was beaten 4-6 3-6 3-6 by
American Richey Reneberg to leave South African Wayne Ferreira as
the only remaining seed in the bottom quarter of the draw.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Krajicek almost became the biggest upset
today when he was trailing by a set when his opponent Andrei Pavel
of Romania suffered injury, granting the fourth seed a surprise
victory 3-6 6-4 6-7 6-3 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, World number one Pete Sampras and two German
veterans Boris Becker and Michael Stich cruised into the next
round by defeating their opponents in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
In the women's singles, World number one Martina Hingis of
Switzerland, ninth seed Mary Pearce of France and other major
seeds also overwhelmed their opponents and sailed into the third
round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
