<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Courts Protect Overseas Clients' Interests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 29 (Xinhua) -- A Hong Kong businessman, who had 13
tons of dried mushrooms that were held illegally by a food company
in Zhangzhou City in east China's Fujian Province, got a fair
hearing from the local court, which saved him more than 120,000
yuan (14,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Courts at various levels in the province, one of China's
coastal areas that are benefiting from the opening-up policy, have
had similar equitable and speedy trials in more than 260 cases
involving Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan compatriots.
</P>
<P>
The cases mostly involved divorces, real estate, and property
and rental disputes with overseas joint-ventures, with real estate
development, sales, and management disputes becoming much more
common.
</P>
<P>
Cases involving Hong Kong, Taiwan and Macao compatriots usually
are given priority for court dates, hearing, and settlement. Some
of them are even handled the very day they are filed.
</P>
<P>
This of course saves overseas compatriots time and money, and
is not bad for the reputation of the local courts either. 
</P>
</TEXT>
