<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece: New Europe Should Not Ignore Small </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 28 (Xinhua) -- The course towards a federal Europe
should not ignore the particularities of the smaller countries,
Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis said while addressing a group
of socialist finance ministers from European Union (EU) member
states.
</P>
<P>
The EU socialist ministers are meeting here this weekend to
discuss strengthening of the social state, accelerating growth and
boosting employment in the EU.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that flexibility should not constitute the main
focus, saying that this would lead to "a concentration of power in
the hands of the bigger states."
</P>
<P>
In short, flexibility would allow some countries to forge ahead
of others, adopting specific policies and integrating more
closely, without the threat of a veto from an unwilling partner.
</P>
<P>
As for economic policy related issues, he stressed the need for
social cohesion, adding that the European socialists should focus
economic policy on battling unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Economic policy should also take into serious consideration
the particularities and sensitivities of the various member-states
of the European Union, he said.
</P>
<P>
Jacques Delors, former European Commission president, also said
at the meeting that the great challenge for socialists was to make
the necessary adjustments to the system, without losing the values
of freedom, solidarity and personal responsibility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
